<DOC><DOCNO> AP880915-0067 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 0609EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     09-15 0507</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0520</SECOND><HEAD>Thunderstorms Lash Texas Panhandle; Apparent Tornado in Amarillo</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Severe thunderstorms unrelated to Hurricane Gilbert lashed theTexas Panhandle today with strong winds and torrential rains andspawned an apparent tornado in Amarillo.   Hurricane Gilbert's outer reaches kept rain and thunderstormsover southern Florida and the Keys. The hurricane moved offMexico's Yucatan Peninsula into the Gulf of Mexico, where its 120mph winds were expected to strengthen, and a hurricane watch wasposted for the entire Texas coast.   The Texas Panhandle storms dropped up to 5 inches of rain southof Amarillo late Wednesday and today. The rain pushed Lake Bennettover its shores and flooded roads around Amarillo with up to 5 feetof water.   The storms generated 60 mph gusts and produced golf-ball sizehail. About a dozen homes were damaged in southwest Amarillo whereresidents reported sighting a tornado late Wednesday.   Showers and a few thunderstorms also extended across westernKansas and eastern Colorado into western Nebraska and overnortheast North Carolina. A band of showers extended from westernMissouri and eastern Kansas to eastern North Dakota.   Today's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstormsover the eastern Gulf of Mexico region and Florida; showers andthunderstorms over the northern and central Plains, the upperMississippi Valley, northwest Missouri and Oklahoma; and widelyscattered showers in northwest Washington state. The rest of thecountry was predicted to have mostly sunny skies.   Highs were forecast to be in the 50s over northern New England;in the 60s along the Pacific Coast, the central Rockies, thenorthern Plains, the upper Mississippi Valley and from the northernGreat Lakes to southern New England; in the 90s in southernFlorida, the lower Mississippi Valley, Texas and the inlandCalifornia valleys; and near 100 degrees in the desert Southwest.Highs elsewhere were expected to be in the 70s and 80s.   Early morning temperatures ranged from the 30s and 40s in theGreat Lakes, central and northern Plains and northern Rockies tothe 60s and 70s from the southern Plains and lower and middleMississippi Valley to the southern Atlantic Coast and lower 80s insouthern Florida.   At 3 a.m. EDT, temperatures ranged from 35 degrees at Marquette,Mich., to 83 degrees at Fort Lauderdale and West Palm Beach, Fla.   Other reports:   _East: Atlanta 76 fair; Boston 59 fair; Buffalo 50 fair;Charleston, S.C. 75 fair; Cleveland 59 fair; Detroit 54 fair; Miami83 partly cloudy; New York 65 fair; Philadelphia 62 fair;Pittsburgh 57 fair; Portland, Me. 52 fair; Washington 64 fair.   _Central: Bismarck 54 rain; Dallas-Fort Worth 73 cloudy; Denver47 fair; Des Moines 64 rain; Indianapolis 61 fair; Kansas City 69showers; Minneapolis-St. Paul 62 cloudy; Nashville 68 fair; NewOrleans 79 partly cloudy; St. Louis 70 fair.   _West: Albuquerque 58 fair; Anchorage 42 fair; Las Vegas 69fair; Los Angeles 62 fair; Phoenix 80 fair; Salt Lake City 49 fair;San Diego 66 cloudy; San Francisco 54 fair; Seattle 52 fair.   _Canada: Montreal 43 fair; Toronto 46 fair.</TEXT></DOC>